        <name>23.6.4 Complex FS Task 3</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
Find the complex Fourier series of the periodic function:
\[ f(t)=e^t \qquad -\pi &amp;lt; t &amp;lt; \pi \hspace{1cm} f(t+2\pi)=f(t)\]&lt;p&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p style="text-align: center;"&gt;&lt;img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/23-6-4%20e%5Et.svg" alt="e^t" width="547" height="176" class="img-responsive atto_image_button_text-bottom"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\(f(t) = \displaystyle{\sum_{n=-\infty}^\infty}\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>We have, since \(T=2\pi\), so \(\omega_0=1\)
\[ 
\begin{align}
c_n &amp;amp; =\frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi}^\pi e^te^{-i nt} dt \\
&amp;amp;= \frac{1}{2\pi}\int_{-\pi}^\pi e^{(1- in)t}dt=\frac{1}{2\pi}\left[\frac{e^{(1- in)t}}{(1- in)}\right]_{-\pi}^\pi \\
&amp;amp;=\frac{1}{2\pi}\frac{1}{(1- in)}\left(e^{(1-in)\pi}-e^{-(1- in)\pi}\right)
\end{align}
\]
Now simplify this as far as possible and write out the Fourier series:
\[ e^{(1- in)\pi}=e^\pi\ e^{- in\pi}=e^\pi (\cos
n\pi- i\sin n\pi)=e^\pi\cos n\pi \]
\[ e^{-(1-in)\pi}=e^{-\pi}e^{ in\pi}=e^{-\pi}\cos n\pi \]
Hence  \( c_n=\dfrac{1}{2\pi}\dfrac{1}{(1- in)}(e^\pi-e^{-\pi})\cos
n\pi=\dfrac{\sinh\pi}{\pi}\dfrac{(1+ in)}{(1+n^2)}\cos n\pi\).
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
Note that the coefficients \(c_n\) \(n=\pm 1,\pm 2,\ldots\) have both real and
imaginary parts in this case as the function being expanded is neither even nor odd.
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
Also \( c_{-n}=\dfrac{\sinh \pi}{\pi}\dfrac{(1-in)}{(1+(-n)^2)}\cos (-n\pi)=\dfrac{\sinh
\pi}{\pi}\dfrac{(1-in)}{(1+n^2)}\cos n\pi={c^*_n}\) as required. 
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
This includes the constant term \(c_0=\dfrac{\sinh \pi}{\pi}.\)
Hence the required Fourier series is
\[ f(t)=\frac{\sinh \pi}{\pi}\sum_{n=-\infty}^\infty (-1)^n\frac{(1+\text{ i}n)}{(1+n^2)} e^{\text{ i}nt}\qquad \text{ since}\quad \cos n\pi=(-1)^n \]</generalfeedback>
